Role: You are an expert Python developer specializing in Flask web applications and precise PDF manipulation using PyMuPDF (fitz).
Context: I have an existing Flask application with various tools. I need to add a new tool that processes Amazon shipping label PDFs uploaded by users.
The Problem: Users upload multiple A4-sized PDF files containing Amazon shipping labels. Currently, each page is divided into 4 quadrants:
Top-Left: Shipping Label 1
Top-Right: Tax Invoice 1
Bottom-Left: Shipping Label 2
Bottom-Right: Tax Invoice 2
(Note: Sometimes an input page might only have 1 label/invoice at the top, leaving the bottom blank).
The Goal: 1. Discard all invoices (the right halves) to save paper.
2. Extract the left halves (the shipping labels) from all uploaded PDFs, and pack them tightly onto new A4 pages (placing one left-half on the left of a new A4 page, and the next left-half on the right of that same A4 page).
3. NEW REQUIREMENT: I need to stamp a small, sequential numeric identifier (1, 2, 3, etc.) on each individual shipping label.
Technical Requirements:
Multiple Uploads: The Flask route must accept multiple PDF file uploads simultaneously from a form (request.files.getlist).
Combine & Process: Merge all uploaded PDFs in the order they were uploaded.
Dimension Calculation (A4 Size):
Standard A4 dimensions in points: width = 595.28, height = 841.89.
Original Left Half Box to crop: (0, 0, 297.64, 841.89)
Transformation Logic (The "Cut and Paste"):
Extract/crop the left half of each page from the combined PDF.
Create a new blank A4 PDF document.
Place the first extracted left half on the left half (0, 0, 297.64, 841.89) of the new Page 1.
Place the second extracted left half on the right half (297.64, 0, 595.28, 841.89) of the new Page 1.
Continue this process for all pages.
Sequential Number Stamping (Crucial):
Each left half actually contains two labels (Top Label and Bottom Label).
You must iterate through the labels and insert a sequential text number (1, 2, 3...) onto the PDF using fitz.
Placement: The number needs to be stamped in the blank space located in the lower-middle-right section of the label (below the "Customer Self Declaration" table and above the bottom routing barcode box like "MASA MMAA").
Provide the stamping logic using easily configurable X and Y coordinate variables (e.g., LABEL_1_TEXT_X, LABEL_1_TEXT_Y) so I can fine-tune the exact pixel placement later.
Make the font size small and subtle (e.g., fontsize 12 or 14).
Output: Save the final combined and reformatted PDF to an in-memory buffer (io.BytesIO) and return it as a downloadable file to the user using Flask's send_file with a filename like optimized_shipping_labels.pdf.
